Fresh-eyes review complete on `src/blog/people/drafts/Christopher-Nolan.md` — notes appended as a `FRESH EYES REVIEW (2026-07-22)` block at the bottom of the file. No body edits made.

**The two biggest issues flagged:**

1. **The Dark Knight is missing.** The timeline jumps 2005 → 2014, and the film that made Nolan a titan — plus Heath Ledger's death, the posthumous Oscar, and the Best Picture snub that changed Academy rules — appears only as one word in the dead-wives inventory. It's the most conspicuous hole for any reader who knows Nolan, and Ledger is the career's one unavoidable grief event, a natural interior beat the draft never touches.

2. **Emma Thomas is never identified as his wife, and the four kids go unstated** — despite fatherhood being a load-bearing theme (Flora's Letter, "spoke to me as a father"). The reader has to infer the marriage from "the woman from his first week at university."

Also worth noting: I flagged **The Prestige** (a whole film about magicians who die rather than reveal the trick, unmentioned in a piece centered on demystification) and the **Tenet COVID-release controversy** (the one place his theatrical crusade drew real criticism — currently the streaming-war section is the only one where critics get no voice) as expansions, and the over-dense banking/ledger metaphor (~10 instances) plus the every-section mic-drop cadence as trims.

The draft's core is strong — the Zimmer cold open, the reverse timeline, the "no great Oz" center, and the Leicester Square ending loop are all worth protecting in the next pass.
